Extended Biography
Sco B. Weingart is a leader, federal policy maker,
and award-winning solar building a thoughtful
future through human-centered tenology. Before
direing initiatives across academic, cultural, and
public seors, he spent time as a hiorian, a librarian, a
data scienti, and (really) a professional circus
performer.
Weingart serves as the Chief Data Ocer and Founding
Direor of the Oce of Data and Evaluation (ODE) at
the National Endowment for the Humanities (NEH).
In his capacity as Chief Data Ocer and as a member of
NEH’s senior leadership team, Weingart oversees data
operations, compliance, analysis, and rategy at the
federal agency. Under Weingart’s direion, the ODE
supports NEH data-informed decision making and
keeps the public informed on the ate of the
humanities in the United States. It does so through
assessments of grant programs for equitability and
impa; through humanities aivities reports to the
White House, Congress, and the public; and through
ongoing partnerships with non-prot, governmental,
resear, and educational organizations.
In addition to his NEH service, Weingart is a Resear
Aliate with the University of Edinburgh’s Centre
for Data, Culture & Society; an Advisory Commiee
Member of the Library of Congress Copyright Public
Modernization Commiee; and an Advisory Board
Member of the Posen Digital Library of Jewish Culture
and Civilization. He formerly direed the University of
Notre Dame’s Navari Family Center for Digital
Solarship and Carnegie Mellon University’s Digital
Humanities program. In both roles, Weingart led large
teams pursuing and supporting the critical use of
emerging tenologies by solars, librarians, and
udents across disciplines. He served in these roles
while maintaining an aive resear and teaing
portfolio. Weingart previously served as a treasurer for
the Alliance of Digital Humanities Organizations and
an executive council member of the Association for
Computers and the Humanities.
Weingart is a prize-
winning author of dozens
of books and articles. e
Network Turn—published
by Cambridge University
Press in 2020 and co-authored with Ruth Ahnert,
Sebaian Ahnert, and Nicole Coleman—is a manifeo
for adoption of network approaes and metaphors in
the humanities. A special issue of the Journal of Literary
eory is dedicated to the book’s central claim. e
Htorian’s Macroscope: Exploring Big Htorical
Data—published by Imperial College Press in 2014 and
co-authored with Shawn Graham, Ian Milligan—is a
popular introduory textbook for digital hiory. e
book introduced the now-common term ‘macroscope’
to the digital humanities community, and it proved
successful enough to warrant an updated edition in
2022 (with added author Kim Martin). Weingart’s
work has been translated into and published in
Chinese, Dut, Italian, Portuguese, Russian,
Spanish, & Ukrainian.
e Alliance of Digital Humanities Organizations
awarded the preigious Paul Fortier Prize in Digital
Humanities to Weingart and his colleague Jeana
Jorgensen in 2011. Weingart’s resear has been funded
by the National Initutes of Health, the National
Science Foundation, the National Endowment for the
Humanities, the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation, and
the Gey Foundation, and his work has been featured
in su publications as the Proceedings of the National
Academy of Scienc, Nunci, Digital Studi / Le amp
numérique, Erkenntn, the Journal of the Aociation for
Information Science & Tenolo, the Journal of
Araeological Method & eory, Scientometrics,
Literary & Lingutic Computing, Cybermetrics, and the
International Journal of Humaniti & Arts Computing.
e common thread running through Weingart’s
multifaceted career is the promotion of a more
equitable, ethical, impaful, and intelleually
sound solarly landscape.
